    "body": "\"That should mean that the above case with axis=0 should have [0,1,2] as index, doesn't it?\"\n\nIt doesn't mean the output should have that index, it means that `len`, the function, is passed a Series object having index with [0,1,2]:\n\n```\n>>> def f(x):\n...     print(x)\n...     return x\n... \n>>> df.apply(f, axis=0)\n0    C\n1    C\n2    A\nName: a, dtype: object\n0    C\n1    C\n2    A\nName: a, dtype: object\n0    C\n1    C\n2    A\nName: b, dtype: object\n0    C\n1    A\n2    A\nName: c, dtype: object\n0    C\n1    A\n2    A\nName: d, dtype: object\n   a  b  c  d\n0  C  C  C  C\n1  C  C  A  A\n2  A  A  A  A\n\n[3 rows x 4 columns]\n```\n\nIt's just like `ones((3,4)).sum(axis=0)` -- you act on `axis=0`, so you're left with `axis=1`, for a shape of `(4,)`.\n"
